The falling pound

The UK's silver-lining post-2008 was the falling pound with its ability to boost the economy. This still isn't the case however. The numbers of people buying British cars such as Nissan Jukes and Volkswagen golf tsi based on good exchange rates has dwindled over the past five years.

This is thankfully, a trend that has not yet been noticed across the pond, but it still makes one wary of investing in a country that can turn so rapidly on a tool of its existence.

How to interpret the fall

It is important to remember that the falling pound has to do with the more important, for the USA anyway, plummeting of the Euro. Not only this, but it gets worse due to the increase of a lowly Chinese Yuan.

The rise of foreign owned businesses has hit UK profits massively over the past six months and when this in conjunction with Brexit concerns major presences such as Ford and Boeing by moving their workers out of the country, things begin to get hairy with skyrocketing inflation on the horizon.

With Brexit woes and seemingly inadequate leadership the hard Brexit that many people felt was prevented has become feasible on behalf of the Conservative party.

The concerns over leaving the single European market has hit home and buyers have begun to take notice to the plight of the pound by shifting their priorities towards US cars.
